etymologies: early 17th century; earliest use found in John Florio (1553–1625), author and teacher of languages. From (i) Middle French, French †exinanition

definitions: The action or process of emptying or exhausting something material or immaterial; the state of being emptied or exhausted, exhaustion.

Chiefly in religious language. The action or process of emptying oneself or another of pride, self-will, or dignity; abasement, humiliation; an instance of this; a state of humiliation. . Of Christ, with reference to Philippians 2:8.
